Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Halve @demi-baguette{2} lengthwise.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle}, half the @garlic powder{1/2%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, combine shallot, @red wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, 1⁄2 tsp @sugar{1/2%tsp}, and 1⁄2 tsp salt (1 tsp sugar and 1 tsp salt for 4 servings). Cover tightly with #plastic wrap{} and microwave until shallot is softened, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir, then refrigerate until ready to use in Step 5.

Pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with remaining @garlic powder{1/2%teaspoon}, a big pinch of salt, and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add beef and cook to desired doneness, ~{4-7%minutes} per side.

In the last minute of cooking, add half the @garlic herb butter{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest later). Baste the beef by gently tilting the pan and spooning melted butter over beef.

Turn off heat; transfer beef to a #cutting board{} to rest.

While beef cooks, in a #large bowl{}, toss @arugula{2%ounce} with @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, 1 tsp shallot pickling liquid, a pinch of @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{}.

Spread remaining garlic herb butter onto cut sides of bottom halves of baguettes. Place @gouda cheese{2%slice} on cut sides of top halves. Place baguette halves, cut sides up, on a second baking sheet; bake on middle rack until cheese melts and bread is toasted, ~{2-4%minutes}.

In a second #small bowl{}, whisk @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon} with as much @truffle seasoning{2%g} as you like.

Thinly slice beef against the grain.

Spread @creamy horseradish sauce{1.5%ounce} on bottom halves of baguettes. Top with sliced beef, as much salad as you like, as much picked shallot as you like (draining first), and @?crispy fried onions{1}. Close halves to form sandwiches.

Divide beef tenderloin sandos and potato wedges between plates. Serve with truffle mayo for dipping and any remaining salad on the side.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.